S. African Stocks: Anglo, Ellies, Metair, Pan African, WG Wearne

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-02-22T16:26:38Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-22/south-african-stocks-fall-most-in-more-than-3-weeks-led-by-anglo-american.html
  South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index dropped to the lowest level since Feb. 10, shedding
362.47, or 1.1 percent, to 32,444.20 at the 5 p.m. close in
Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.    Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the diversified mining company
that makes up 11 percent of South Africa’s benchmark stock
index, slumped to the lowest level since Feb. 1, slipping 2.55
rand, or 0.7 percent, to 371 rand. Copper fell to a three-week
low on concern surging  oil prices  may slow economic growth,
curbing demand for the metal used in wires and plumbing.    Ellies Holdings Ltd . (ELI SJ), a manufacturer of satellite
television equipment, snapped three days of losses, advancing 5
cents, or 2.4 percent, to 2.12 rand. Ellie Salkow and Raymond
Berkman, chairman and executive director of the company
respectively, purchased a combined 7 million rand ($980,000)
worth of shares in the company.    Metair Investments Ltd . (MTA SJ), rallied to the highest
level since May 2008, climbing 60 cents, or 4.8 percent, to
13.10 rand. The company said in a statement it expects earnings
per share for the year ended 31 December 2010 to be between 1.83
rand and 1.96 rand, compared with 67 cents for the previous
corresponding period.    Pan African Resources Plc  (PAN SJ), a gold exploration
company, climbed to the highest level since Nov. 12, advancing 4
cents, or 3.3 percent, to 1.24 rand. The company said earnings
per share increased 56 percent to 0.53 pence in the first half
through December, from 0.34 pence a year earlier.  WG Wearne Ltd. (WEA SJ), a South African concrete maker,
dropped to the lowest level since listing in 2006, shedding 6
cents, or 30 percent, to 14 cents. The company agreed in
principle to a 65.2 million-rand loan from the state-owned
Industrial Development Corp., subject to the company
successfully executing its debt moratorium announced last week,
and a disposal of a subsidiary, Portland Holdings Ltd., the
company said in a statement today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
